===Etymology===
From {{etyl|la}} {{term|abscissio|abscissio|lang=la}}, from {{term|abscindo|abscindo|to cut or tear|lang=la}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/æbˈsɪ.ʃn̩/|/æbˈsɪ.ʒn̩/}}

===Noun===
{{examples-right|sense=rhetoric|examples=He is a man of so much honor and [[candor]], and of such [[generosity]] -- but I need say no more.}}
{{en-noun}}

# The act or process of cutting off.
#* '''1859''', [[w:Jeremy Taylor|Jeremy Taylor]], ''The sermons of the Right Rev. Jeremy Taylor: Complete in one volume'', page 286:
#*: Not to be cured without the '''abscission''' of a member.
# {{obsolete}} The state of being cut off. {{defdate|Attested only in the mid 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}
# {{context|rhetoric}} A figure of speech employed when a [[speaker]] having [[begun]] to say a thing stops [[abruptly]]
# {{botany}} The natural separation of a part at a predetermined location, such as a [[leaf]] at the base of the [[petiole]]. {{defdate|First attested in the late 19<sup>th</sup> century.}

====Usage notes====
Not to be confused with [[abscision]], which only is defined as the first sense.

